<h2 id="the-two-fund-theorem-and-the-capm">The two fund theorem and the CAPM</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>We now move to equilibrium considerations. We assume all investors share the same beliefs on expected returns and risk, and all choose mean variance efficient portfolios.</p></li>
<li><p>As a result, they all hold a mixture of the risk free asset and a unique portfolio of risky asset, the tangency portfolio.</p></li>
<li><p>This is an instance of the two fund theorem, which also holds in more general contexts</p></li>
<li><p>The risky asset portfolio should be equal to the market portfolio of risky asset, with return <span class="math inline">\(r_{m}\)</span>. This gives: <span class="math display">\[(\mu_{i}-r^{f})=(\mu_{m}-r^{f})\beta (\tilde{r}_{i},\tilde{r}_{m}).\]</span></p></li>
</ul>
